<section xml:id="section-TFSC">
    <title>Misc Applications of Calculus (WIP)</title>

    <subsection>
        <title>Applications of Calculus</title>
        <p>
            Broadly, calculus is a supporting player that works in the background of science.
        </p>
    </subsection>

    <ul>
        <li>Mathematical physics.</li>
        <li>Engineering.</li>
        <li>Chemistry.</li>
        <li>Astronomy.</li>
        <li>Economics. Finance. Business. Curves modelling stock prices. How can one predict the effect of interest rate changes on economies and stock markets?</li>
        <li>Statistics.</li>
        <li>Medicine. Curves modelling blood pressure.</li>
    </ul>

    <ul>
        <li>Newton's laws of motion.</li>
        <li>Why do hurricane winds spiral counterclockwise in the northern hemisphere?</li>
        <li>When will radioactive material be sufficiently decayed to enable safe handling?</li>
        <li>How do warm ocean currents in the equatorial Pacific affect the climate of eastern North America?</li>
        <li>How long will the concentration of a drug in the bloodstream remain at effective levels? Rate of change in the amount of drug at a particular time (i.e. drug absorption). How small changes in dosage affect body's response to a drug.</li>
        <li>Why does an epidemic spread faster and faster and then slow down?</li>
        <li>How can I be sure that the bridge I designed won't be destroyed in a windstorm?</li>
        <li>Calculus is the foundation of traffic flow.</li>
        <li>Calculus is a hidden supporting player behind many modern technologies, including radio, TV, microwave ovens, computers, GPS, putting astronauts on the moon, ultrasound, splitting the atom, unraveling the human genome (Steven Strogatz).</li>
        <li>Applications to electric fields and electric force, magnetic field, James Clerk Maxwell (1860s), Maxwell's equations in the language of differential equations (calculus). Led to the technologies of wireless communication. Michael Faraday and Andre-Marie Ampere (experimental physics).</li>
        <li>Predator-prey systems.</li>
        <li>Harvesting of populations (sustainable harvesting?). Survival and renewal of resources.</li>
        <li>Calculus describes the rhythm of the tides?</li>
        <li>Calculus describes how the flow of air allows a hummingbird to fly.</li>
        <li>Applications to listening to music on smartphones (waves?), and laser checkout scanner at the supermarket.</li>
        <li>Applications to trajectory design for the space program, differential equations used to calculate trajectories.</li>
        <li>Rosalind Franklin, used Fourier analysis to study the patterns that x-rays make after they bounce off of DNA molecules, which led to the structure of DNA.</li>
        <li>Current is the rate of change in change with respect to time, at a particular time.</li>
        <li>Geology.</li>
        <li>Rate of change of temperature over time.</li>
        <li>Applications of differential equations: Newton’s second law of motion, Newton’s laws, fluid mechanics, elasticity, economic and social systems, biological population dynamics, electrical systems, gossip spreading, ability to absorb vitamins, cold virus spreading, planetary orbit, bacterial colony, continuously compounding interest, Hooke’s law, cell division.</li>
    </ul>
</section>